---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'About StateWages — Why This Site Exists';
const description = 'StateWages was built out of frustration with salary sites that hide real data behind paywalls and surveys. Here\'s the story behind it and how the data works.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="about-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">About this site</span>
      <h1>Why I Built This</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <main>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-content">

        <div class="about-body">

          <p class="lead">
            A few years ago I was trying to figure out whether to take a job offer in another state.
            The salary seemed good, but I had no clean way to tell if it was actually good <em>for that market</em>.
          </p>

          <p>
            I spent an embarrassing amount of time on Glassdoor, Indeed, and Payscale — and every single one
            of them either hid the real numbers behind a login, showed me "estimated" ranges based on
            self-reported surveys from 12 people, or pushed me toward some premium subscription to
            see anything useful. The BLS website had the actual government data I needed, but navigating
            it felt like reading a tax form. Rows of spreadsheet. No context. No comparison.
          </p>

          <p>
            The data I wanted was public. The federal government collects it every year, for free,
            for every occupation in every state. It was just buried.
          </p>

          <p>
            So I built StateWages to fix that for myself — and figured other people probably run into
            the same wall.
          </p>

          <h2>Where the data comes from</h2>

          <p>
            Every number on this site comes directly from the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics
            Occupational Employment and Wage Statistics (OEWS) program. BLS surveys roughly
            1.1 million businesses every year, covering 800+ occupations across all 50 states
            plus DC. The May 2024 data (the most recent release) is what powers this site right now.
          </p>

          <p>
            I download the raw data file from bls.gov, run it through a processing script, and
            generate a page for every occupation-state combination that has enough data to report.
            When BLS releases new data each May, I update the site within a few days. That's it.
            No surveys. No estimates. No employer-submitted numbers that may or may not reflect reality.
          </p>

          <p>
            The tradeoff is that BLS data is a snapshot — it reflects conditions from the survey period,
            not today's job market. And BLS suppresses data when the sample size for a given occupation
            in a given state is too small to report reliably, which is why some pages show "N/A" for
            certain percentiles. That's not a bug. That's the data telling you it doesn't have enough
            observations to give you a number worth trusting.
          </p>

          <h2>What the percentiles actually mean</h2>

          <p>
            A lot of people look at the "median" and stop there. The percentile breakdown is more
            useful than most people realize:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>10th percentile</strong> — what someone just starting out, or working in a low-paying market, typically earns</li>
            <li><strong>25th percentile</strong> — early-career or smaller employer range</li>
            <li><strong>Median (50th)</strong> — the middle of the market. Half earn more, half earn less.</li>
            <li><strong>75th percentile</strong> — experienced workers, larger employers, higher-cost areas</li>
            <li><strong>90th percentile</strong> — top of the market. Senior roles, specialized skills, major metros.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            When you're negotiating a salary, knowing where a number falls in that range matters
            a lot more than knowing the average.
          </p>

          <h2>What this site is not</h2>

          <p>
            This is not a job board. I'm not trying to sell you a resume service or
            connect you with recruiters. There are no surveys to fill out, no accounts to create,
            and no premium tiers. The data is public and the site is free because there's no
            reason it shouldn't be.
          </p>

          <p>
            The site runs display ads to cover hosting costs and my time. That's the whole business model.
          </p>

          <div class="about-note">
            <strong>A note on accuracy:</strong> I cross-check the data against BLS's own published
            tables periodically, but if you spot a number that looks wrong, the most likely explanation
            is a data suppression issue or a rounding difference. The raw source is always
            <a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bls.gov/oes</a> —
            that's the ground truth.
          </div>

        </div>

        <aside class="about-sidebar">
          <div class="info-block">
            <h3>Site facts</h3>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">📊</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Data source</div><div class="info-value">BLS OEWS May 2024</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">🗂️</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Occupations covered</div><div class="info-value">800+</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">🗺️</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">States covered</div><div class="info-value">All 50 + DC</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">📅</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Updated</div><div class="info-value">Annually each May</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">💰</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Cost to use</div><div class="info-value">Free</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="info-block">
            <h3>Useful links</h3>
            <ul class="related-links">
              <li><a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BLS OEWS Program</a></li>
              <li><a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BLS Occupational Outlook Handbook</a></li>
              <li><a href="/privacy-policy/">Privacy Policy</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-hero {
    background: var(--bg-inset);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding: 3rem 0 2.5rem;
  }

  .about-content {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 240px;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    padding: 2.5rem 0 5rem;
  }

  .about-body { max-width: 640px; }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .about-body p { line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1.1rem; }

  .about-body h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .about-body ul { margin-bottom: 1.1rem; }
  .about-body li { line-height: 1.65; margin-bottom: 0.45rem; }

  .about-note {
    background: var(--primary-light);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--primary);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--primary-dark);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .about-sidebar { position: sticky; top: calc(58px + 1rem); }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .about-content { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .about-sidebar { position: static; }
  }
</style>
